        <p class="metadata">Posted by Darby Felton (darby) on 2007-02-22T13:37:59.000+0000</p> 
        <div class="body">
            <p>Though an argument can be made that there appears to be a de facto convention that components be named Zend_[Noun], it is not "official" policy to name components in such a way.</p>

<p>With components named Zend_Config and Zend_Auth, we might have named it Zend_Valid, which was the name I had originally chosen, but Zend_Validate was deemed to be more clear.</p>

<p>With a component named Zend_Filter, notice that the word "filter" has multiple usages, including both noun and verb forms.</p>

<p>I think that changing the name at this point seems to benefit little when compared with the impact such name changes have as uptake of the framework increases and our API change tolerance decreases.</p>

        </div>
    </div>
        <div class="comment">
        <p class="metadata">Posted by Bill Karwin (bkarwin) on 2007-02-22T14:16:37.000+0000</p> 
        <div class="body">
            <p>I agree -- in this case the difference is very minor, and is outweighed by the impact of changing a class name in the core library.  If it were a class that is only called internally by the component it would have less impact, but this is the top-level class of the component and we need to start being careful about backward-compatibility.</p>

<p>We do not have a policy that class names must be nouns.  It's not a bad guideline, but I don't think we need it to be a policy.</p>

        </div>
    </div>
        <div class="comment">
        <p class="metadata">Posted by Matthew Ratzloff (mratzloff) on 2007-02-22T16:59:09.000+0000</p> 
        <div class="body">
            <p>Now, before the beta, would be the time to make any name changes---that is, to create a naming convention policy.  It promotes cohesiveness over the whole framework, and seems to have support from at least some others in the community.  A naming policy is also important for the same reasons that specifying parameter formats (e.g., camelCase), method names (verb or verb+noun), and parameter orders for similar classes.  It increases predictability and lowers the learning curve.</p>

<p>Out of the entire framework, two (maybe three, counting Measure) top-level classes are exceptions out of almost 40 when there's no real reason for it.  The rest of the classes fall into two basic categories:</p>

<ul><li>Concrete nouns (Controller, Filter, etc.)</li>
<li>Generalized nouns, divided into broad topics (Locale, Session, etc.) and specific protocols, formats, and standards (Http, Mime, etc.)</li>
</ul><p>Obviously, I'm a bit more passionate about naming consistency and API clarity than many others, but I think since this affects the user community why not go to them and determine whether they believe a simple naming policy is important, erring on the side of no change?</p>

        </div>
