        <p class="metadata">Posted by Matthew Ratzloff (mratzloff) on 2007-03-09T11:25:18.000+0000</p> 
        <div class="body">
            <p>Hi Darby,</p>

<p>You say that class names were discussed during the proposal period.  When did this discussion take place?  Who was involved?  Was it strictly an internal vote that was taken?  I ask because I've actually taken the time to dig through mailing list archives and proposal comments, and here is what I've come up with:</p>

<h1>Art Hundiak first mentioned a revised validator.  He called it Zend_Validate.  (He would later use Zend_Validator instead.)</h1>

<h1>A couple months later, in the Zend_FilterChain proposal, Willie Alberty referred to it once as Zend_Validate in passing.</h1>

<h1>Every person who referred to the concept since the initial proposal and afterward, in his thread and elsewhere—and I mean every single person without exception—called it Zend_Validator.</h1>

<h1>You proposed Zend_Valid.</h1>

<h1>Even after this proposal, most referred to it as Zend_Validator in the comments on the proposal page and in the mailing list.  Less frequently, Zend_Valid (using your initial name) was used.</h1>

<p>Unless I'm missing it (and it's possible), at no point did anyone say that they preferred the name Zend_Validate.  Instead, overwhelmingly, Zend_Validator was used again and again.  Clearly, the community prefers the name Zend_Validator, or feels that it's more intuitive.</p>

<p>The recent discussion over the refactored Zend.php has also shown that the community cares about naming when they have a choice.  It's stated that this change would be too costly for 0.9.0, yet Bill just removed the Zend.php class entirely, requiring everyone with existing applications to do a search and replace for Zend::loadClass(), Zend::loadFile(), Zend::isReadable(), Zend::debug(), Zend::register(), Zend::registry(), Zend::isRegistered(), Zend::initRegistry(), and possibly one or two others I'm forgetting.  Why is an additional search and replace for Zend_Validate and Zend_Translate, which are not static and therefore actually occur less than the previous instances, prohibitively costly?  A class in core has already changed for 0.9.0.  Renaming these classes is a simple matter of searching and replacing.</p>

<p>Many of these naming issues are coming up because this is the period before 0.9.0—when whatever names we have we're stuck with.  This is the best time to make these changes.  I just don't want to see Zend Framework become like PHP, with names that were chosen with little or no concern for naming.  I won't reopen the issue, but I urge you to reconsider.</p>

        </div>
    </div>
        <div class="comment">
        <p class="metadata">Posted by Darby Felton (darby) on 2007-03-09T12:27:32.000+0000</p> 
        <div class="body">
            <p>Please allow me to clarify. During internal discussions at Zend, Andi indicated his preference for using the name Validate over the other available choices, and there was no dissent over the decision.</p>

<p>It is not a fair comparison to make between this suggested change and the recent changes to Zend.php. The latter changes to Zend.php offered value beyond simple name changes. Unrelated functionality that had been lumped together in a "catch-all", miscellaneous class is now logically separated. This suggested change offers no value beyond a slightly improved name, which, in itself, is debatable.</p>

<p>Again, I'm not saying the name can never be changed. In fact, I agree that Zend_Validator would probably be a better name. But timing is everything, and it is not the right time to do this now. There is life after 0.9.0, I promise! :)</p>

